{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox company | name = Bath Cabinet Makers Ltd. | logo = | logo_caption = | image = Bath Cabinet Makers factory.jpg | image_size = 220 | image_caption = Bath Cabinet Makers factory in Bellotts Road, Twerton. Built 1895. | trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above --> | native_name = Bath and West Co-operative Cabinet Makers Ltd | native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. "fr" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. --> | romanized_name = | former type = | type = Privately held company | traded_as = Bath Cabinet Makers | industry = Furniture makers | genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies --> | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = <!-- City, Country ({{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}) --> | founder = Charles A Richter | defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location_city = [[Twerton]], [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] | location_country = England | locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. --> | area_served = | key_people = | products = | production = | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies --> | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = | bodystyle = }} '''Bath Cabinet Makers Ltd.''' traded for sixty-seven years (1892–1959){{sfn|Festing|1998|p=146}} in a city, [[Bath, Somerset]], England, with a history of furniture-making.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Furniture Made in Bath|journal=Holbourne Museum Exhibition Catalogue|date=1985}}</ref> Under management of Charles A Richter (1876–1945) until 1934, its work was regularly illustrated in ''[[The Studio (magazine)|The Studio]]'' and the company soon began to receive international prizes.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=157}} A variety of styles was produced, from Parisian-inspired versions of 'Adam' to [[Art Nouveau]], [[Art Deco]], [[Arts and Crafts]] and streamlined Modern in a huge range of woods, solid and veneer.{{sfn|Payne|1981|p=23}} Important contracts included furniture and fittings for [[Cunard]]'s luxury liners, the [[RMS Queen Mary|Queen Mary]] and [[RMS Queen Elizabeth|Queen Elizabeth]]. A proportion of its output was mass-produced for cheaper markets although the workmanship was always of a high standard.
==History== Built in 1895, the factory on Bellots Road, [[Twerton]] was one of the largest and best equipped in the country.{{sfn|Payne|1981|p=23}} Bath Timber Supply Ltd and Bath Guild of Handicraft and Design were set up in the 1920s to support Bath Cabinet Makers. George Montague Elwood was responsible for many of the [[Art Nouveau]] pieces around 1899–1900, but most of Bath Cabinet Makers's furniture was designed by the Richter brothers, Charles Augustus (1867–1946), Herbert Davis (1874–1955) and their team.{{sfn|Payne|1981|p=23}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Bath Cabinet Makers|url=http://www.marvellousfurniture.co.uk/bathcabinetmakers.html|publisher=The Marvellous Furniture co|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Charles Richter became president of the National Federation of Furniture Trades{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=162}} and was appointed to [[Baron Gorell|Lord Gorell's]] Commission on improving the standard of art in industry.<ref name=Richter /> In JC Rogers' Modern English Furniture (1930) he is one of forty-two designers listed beside the better-known [[Barnsley brothers|Barnsleys]] and [[Edwin Lutyens]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=JC|title=Modern English Furniture|journal=Country Life Publications|date=1930}}</ref>
Bath Cabinet Makers owed its existence to a strike at F and A Norris Brothers' Bath's Albion Cabinet Works in December 1891. The following year, Charles Richter, an employee at Albion, launched the Bath and West Co-operative Cabinet Makers Ltd. The intention was determinedly idealistic; men needed jobs and the city provided enterprise. Shareholders were represented by a committee five members, one of whom was the influential Cedric Chivers from the bookbinding family. Richter was elected general manager the following month, and work began in rented accommodation.{{sfn|Festing|1998|pp=153–154}}
In 1892 the name was contracted to The Bath Cabinet Makers Ltd. The next year, Charles Richter walked out, objecting to the Shareholders' reluctance to expand. Two years later the Society called him back as managing director, with Herbert Davis Richter Head of the Design Department.<ref>{{cite book|last=Keevil|first=HT|title=History of Bath Cabinet Makers|date=1956|page=17}}</ref> Herbert Davis Richter's drawings were reproduced in all the relevant leading architectural journals.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fell Granville|first=H|title=1900|journal=Art Journal special edition published for the Paris World Exhibition}}</ref> In 1895 the brothers collaborated with Messrs Silcock and Reay on the design of a distinctive new building.{{sfn|Festing|1998|pp=157–158}} In 1900, the firm won five medals at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Paris World Exhibition]].{{sfn|Granville Fell|1935|pp=13–14}}
==Later years== Prior to [[World War I]], Bath Cabinet Makers furniture was on constant display in London stores such as Maples and [[Harrods]].{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=161}} While Herbert Davis Richter left Bath Cabinet Makers in 1906 to become a painter,{{sfn|Granville Fell|1935|p=16}} Charles Richter's hope of early retirement were interrupted by the war. The factories were converted to manufacture aircraft parts, to be restored to panelling, joinery and high-class furniture when the war ended. The family interest was extended when Herbert Davis Richter's wife, Gertrude, and Charles Richter's sister, Florence Schottler, launched The Guild of Handicraft and Design to make soft furnishings for large contracts coming in from America, India and Germany.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=162}} Further recognition was earned at the [[British Empire Exhibition]] at [[Wembley]] of 1924 and the [[International Exposition of Modern Industrial and Decorative Arts|Paris Exhibition]] of 1925.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=162}} CAR's elder son Ian joined the firm in the early 1920s and became managing director in 1934. He produced some fine wood carvings that were used in the setting of BCM furniture, many on the [[RMS Queen Elizabeth|Queen Elizabeth]]. The 1930s depression affected demand for luxury furniture but Charles Richter managed to keep his firm afloat.
==Idealism of Charles A Richter== [[File:Richter table 1.jpg|thumb|Table in walnut with black insets, designed by CA Richter]] [[William Morris]] considered that machines were responsible for bad design. As handwork was necessarily time-consuming, his furniture was too expensive for the very people he wanted to supply. In contrast, Charles Richter, a committed socialist and natural progressive, deplored asking men to perform arduous tasks that could easily be accomplished by machine.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=147}} In Bath Cabinet Makers's early days, he set up an Education Committee and ran games and dramatic clubs.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=157}} Acquainted with [[GB Shaw]], he asked the playwright down to Bath for a performance of Caesar and Cleopatra.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=164}}
==Post-war== In 1959 the firm was taken over by Yatton Furniture, its name and the goodwill lasted for more than a century.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=146}} Plagiarism had been a continual battle. From the outset Bath Cabinet Makers's prolific output and range of styles led to pirating by other companies.{{sfn|Festing|1998|p=160}}<ref name= Richter>{{cite news|title=Obituary: C.A.Richter |newspaper=The Furnishing World|date=1946 | page=80 }}</ref> This has led to much of their work being attributed to other firms. Current research into Wylie & Lochhead and Bath Cabinet Makers reveals that prestigious museums throughout the country have believed that Bath Cabinet Makers furniture was made by the Scottish cabinet-making firm.<ref>Holbourne Museum Bath</ref>
The company became part of the Christie-Tyler furniture group and in 1986 was bought out by Ken Fullalove, one of their directors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bath craftsman honoured for lifetime devoted to furniture making |url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Bath-craftsman-honoured-lifetime-devoted/story-17394070-detail/story.html|accessdate=25 March 2014|newspaper=Bath Chronicle|date=24 November 2012}}</ref>
